.TH "TEMPORAL.PLAINDATE.DAY" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Temporal.PlainDate.day \- Temporal.PlainDate.prototype.day
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]day\f[B]\f[R] accessor property of
\f[CR]Temporal.PlainDate\f[R] instances returns a positive integer
representing the 1\-based day index in the month of this date, which is
the same day number you would see on a calendar.
It is calendar\-dependent.
.PP
It generally starts at 1 and is continuous, but not always.
If you want to loop through all the days in a month, first use
\f[CR]with()\f[R] with \f[CR]{ day: 1 }\f[R] (which sets to the
beginning of the month, even if the actual number is not \f[CR]1\f[R]),
then repeatedly use \f[CR]add()\f[R] with \f[CR]{ days: 1 }\f[R], until
the month changes.
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] Usually, the day index only changes when transitioning
from one calendar system into another, such as \c
.UR https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adoption_of_the_Gregorian_calendar
from the Julian to the Gregorian calendar
.UE \c
\&.
In practice, all currently built\-in calendars are \c
.UR https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proleptic_Gregorian_calendar
proleptic
.UE \c
, meaning the calendar system is extended indefinitely into the past and
future.
Assuming \f[CR]day\f[R] is non\-continuous guards against future
introductions of non\-proleptic calendars.
.RE
.PP
The set accessor of \f[CR]day\f[R] is \f[CR]undefined\f[R].
You cannot change this property directly.
Use the \f[CR]with()\f[R] method to create a new
\f[CR]Temporal.PlainDate\f[R] object with the desired new value.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using day
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] date = Temporal.PlainDate.from(\(dq2021\-07\-01\(dq); \f[I]// ISO 8601 calendar\f[R]
console.log(date.day); \f[I]// 1\f[R]

\f[B]const\f[R] date2 = Temporal.PlainDate.from(\(dq2021\-07\-01[u\-ca=chinese]\(dq);
console.log(date2.day); \f[I]// 22; it is May 22 in the Chinese calendar\f[R]
.EE
.SS Looping through all days in a month
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] month = Temporal.PlainDate.from(\(dq2021\-07\-14\(dq); \f[I]// An arbitrary date in the month\f[R]
\f[B]for\f[R] (
  \f[B]let\f[R] day = month.with({ day: 1 });
  day.month === month.month;
  day = day.add({ days: 1 })
) {
  console.log(day.day);
}
.EE
.SS Changing day
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] date = Temporal.PlainDate.from(\(dq2021\-07\-01\(dq);
\f[B]const\f[R] newDate = date.with({ day: 15 });
console.log(newDate.toString()); \f[I]// 2021\-07\-15\f[R]
.EE
.PP
You can also use \f[CR]add()\f[R] or \f[CR]subtract()\f[R] to move a
certain number of days from the current date.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] date = Temporal.PlainDate.from(\(dq2021\-07\-01\(dq);
\f[B]const\f[R] newDate = date.add({ days: 14 });
console.log(newDate.toString()); \f[I]// 2021\-07\-15\f[R]
.EE
.PP
By default, \f[CR]with()\f[R] constrains the day to the range of valid
values.
So you can use \f[CR]{ day: 1 }\f[R] to set the day to the first day of
the month, even if the first day does not have the number \f[CR]1\f[R].
Similarly, the following will set the day to the last day of the month:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] date = Temporal.PlainDate.from(\(dq2021\-07\-01\(dq);
\f[B]const\f[R] lastDay = date.with({ day: Number.MAX_VALUE }); \f[I]// 2021\-07\-31\f[R]
.EE
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] Avoid using \f[CR]daysInMonth\f[R] to set the day to the
last day of the month.
The last day of the month is not always the same as the number of days
in the month, in the rare case where a month may have a few days
skipped.
.RE
